ce:section.ce:para:
Pan et al. [73] reported an ultrasensitive fluorescent probe (8), which was successfully applied to selectively monitor endogenous NADH and NADPH levels, both in vitro and in vivo. The quinolinium moiety served as the recognition site and the component of the hemicyanine fluorophore (Fig. 7
                        ). Probe 8 displayed weak fluorescence at 604 nm; however, the fluorescence intensity showed a gradual increase with increasing NADH concentrations (0–3 μM), with a detection limit as low as 6 nM. The detection of NADH and NADPH was not affected by the presence of biomolecules, including inorganic salts, amino acids, GSH, SO3
                        2−, H2S2, AA, dithiothreitol (DTT), NAD+, NADP+, FADH2, and ROS. HepaG-2 cells were incubated with 0–50 μM probe 8 for 18 h and retained approximately 90% viability. Subsequently, confocal microscopy was used to analyze probe 8 fluorescence associated with NADH and NADPH in HepG-2 cells under hypoxia and normoxia. The fluorescent signal in the cells was stronger under hypoxic conditions than under normal oxygen conditions, suggesting that more NADH and NADPH had formed in hypoxic cells. When HepG-2 cells were incubated with the natural antioxidant resveratrol (0–10 μg mL−1) for 6 h under hypoxic conditions, the fluorescence signal gradually increased. The fluorescence intensity was almost unchanged under normal oxygen conditions; however, the fluorescence intensity decreased marginally when the HepG-2 cells were treated with 20 μg mL−1 resveratrol. This may have been due to oxidative stress-induced cell death. A similar phenomenon was observed in the presence of curcumin and celastrol, as evidenced by confocal microscopy analysis. Subsequently, tumor-bearing mice were injected with different concentrations of resveratrol (0–30 μg mL−1) at the tumor site for 10 days and then incubated probe 8 (10 μM) for 30 min. The fluorescence signal (using an in vivo imaging system) of probe 8 in the mice was also gradually increased, indicating that NADH and NADPH levels could be monitored during liver cancer treatment in vivo. Moreover, the growth rate of tumor tissue in the mice slowed (as measured using digital calipers) with increasing natural antioxidant concentrations. Treating mice with curcumin and celastrol under the same experimental conditions produced similar results. Together, these findings suggested that natural antioxidants might induce tumor cell death by reducing stress. Furthermore, this study provided a novel idea for the study of natural antioxidants and a new method for the clinical diagnosis and treatment of cancer.
